The measurement data for the extant species ( Tables S1 and S 2 ) used to assess the ecomorphotype of
Aquilolamna milarcae
were assembled from the literature (
,
-
). We followed Sternes and Shimadaʾs (
) strategy by using illustrations of reference books (i.e., FAO publications, authored by experts of international renown) to determine some morphometric measurements usually not provided in the literature and thus not available for all species. Interestingly, Sternes and Shimada (
) demonstrated the high degree of similarity between the book illustrations and actual shark samples, thus showing that such drawings can be reliably used for interspecific morphometric analyses. For each shark species included in the present analysis, illustrations in lateral and ventral views allowed to assess body proportions and to calculate the precaudal length (PCL), caudal fin length (CFL) and pectoral fin span (PFS) on the basis of the known maximum total length (TL). For each batoid species (except rhinopristiform species) included in the present analysis, we used either the known maximum disc width (DW, which corresponds to the PFS of sharks and rhinopristiform batoids) to calculate the disc length (DL), or the known maximum TL to calculate the disc length and disc width (using illustrations in dorsal view). In addition to the measurements of specimen INAH 2544 P.F.17, hypothetical measurements inferred from a 250 cm hypothetical maximum TL were used for
A. milarcae
. All measurements were log 10 -transformed in order to improve normality and homogeneity of variance. All analyses described below were performed using PAleontological STatistics (PAST software, version 4.04) (
).

